What happens internally?

Suppose your setup looks like this:

Your Laptop
    │
    │ kubectl proxy
    │
localhost:8001
    │
    │ HTTPS
    ▼
Kubernetes API Server
    │
    ▼
Dashboard Service

When you open:

http://127.0.0.1:8001

the request flow is:

Your browser sends the request to localhost:8001.
The local kubectl proxy process receives it.
kubectl authenticates to the Kubernetes API Server using the credentials in your kubeconfig.
The API Server processes the request and returns the response through the proxy.
What service is started on the client?

Only one process starts:

kubectl proxy

It creates:

A local HTTP server
Default port: 8001
Listens only on 127.0.0.1 (localhost)

You can verify it's listening.

On Linux:

netstat -tlnp | grep 8001

On Windows:

netstat -ano | findstr 8001

You'll see something like:

TCP 127.0.0.1:8001 LISTENING
How does it know where to send requests?

Your kubeconfig contains:

API Server URL
Client certificate or token
CA certificate

For example:

clusters:
- cluster:
    server: https://192.168.1.10:6443

So the proxy forwards requests to:

localhost:8001
      │
      ▼
https://192.168.1.10:6443
Why is kubectl proxy useful?

Normally, the Dashboard Service is a ClusterIP service:

NAME                     TYPE
kubernetes-dashboard     ClusterIP

A ClusterIP is only accessible inside the cluster.

Without the proxy:

Browser
   │
   X
ClusterIP (not reachable)

With the proxy:

Browser
   │
localhost:8001
   │
kubectl proxy
   │
API Server
   │
Dashboard Service

The proxy bridges your local machine to the cluster through the API Server.

Does it expose the Dashboard directly?

No. The Dashboard is accessed through the Kubernetes API proxy.

The Dashboard URL is typically:

http://127.0.0.1:8001/api/v1/namespaces/kubernetes-dashboard/services/https:kubernetes-dashboard:/proxy/

Notice the path:

API Server
    │
Service
    │
Dashboard

The API Server proxies the request to the Dashboard Service.

Is it secure?

Yes.

Uses your kubeconfig credentials.
Only listens on 127.0.0.1 by default.
Doesn't expose the Dashboard to other machines.
Enforces Kubernetes RBAC based on your identity.
Difference between kubectl proxy and kubectl port-forward
Feature	kubectl proxy	kubectl port-forward
Connects to	Kubernetes API Server	A specific Pod or Service
Uses API Server proxy	Yes	No
Default port	8001	User chooses (e.g., 8080:443)
Requires API path	Yes	No
Common use	Dashboard, API access	Application debugging

For example:

kubectl proxy

Then browse to:

http://127.0.0.1:8001/api/v1/...

Whereas:

kubectl port-forward svc/kubernetes-dashboard 8443:443 -n kubernetes-dashboard

lets you access the Dashboard directly at:

https://127.0.0.1:8443

without going through the API Server proxy.

In summary, kubectl proxy starts a lightweight HTTP server on your local machine that authenticates to the Kubernetes API Server using your kubeconfig and securely proxies your browser's requests to Kubernetes resources, such as the Dashboard. It doesn't install any additional services on your client—it's just the kubectl process acting as a proxy.
